What Separates High-Growth Companies from the Rest
A useful way to think about AI infrastructure's impact on growth is to look at what distinguishes companies that are scaling fast from those that are stagnating. Consider these markers:

High-growth companies in 2026 have unified their first-party data and connected it to real-time intent signals. They run AI models that continuously score and prioritize accounts based on live behavioral data. Their marketing and sales teams operate from a single source of truth, with AI recommendations embedded directly into their workflows. Their content is dynamically personalized and delivered across multiple channels based on where each buyer is in their journey.

Stagnating companies, by contrast, are still relying on manually maintained CRM data, batch-and-blast email campaigns, and siloed marketing and sales operations. They generate leads, but those leads are poorly qualified. They invest in content, but that content is not matched to the right buyer at the right moment.

The difference is not strategy — it is infrastructure.

